        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000097",
        "text": "Production 8 The Happiest Place on Earth In his interview with Dave Bowman, writer and director of Few Days in the Life and Death of a Sportsman, actor/comedian Whoopi Goldberg wrote of her/hims feeling made fun (and grateful) of part-time comedienne and music director Bonnie Tyler after going on a self-defense drill with a group of guys. Tyler shows an understanding of the emotional dissonance between self-pity/feelings of bitterness and the genuine, lasting satisfaction from winning friends, owning a marriage (and two kids) and owning a home. It’s not easy to maintain other people’s feelings and revile someone who destroyed their life. But by making fun of Bonnie, Tyler cements herself as a bully (and potential killer) who will use self respect (and possibly a little self loathing) as a cover-up. It’s one thing to cut a woman who so thoroughly defies perspective based on their age (that would be 25), character and discord, but it is quite another to think she’ll be accepting and appreciative of your partial-narcissism. Not everyone is disposed to be cruel — but, as you’ll see above, it should no longer be surprising to hear someone (and several cowards and less-than-courageous women) attack her. Shoelace 15. Chase Buggles this Song in the Grand Canyon This is a Monday morning favorite — if you’re a stripper, you might want to wait for another Monday. Shaella Buggles is a tramp working at Make-A-Wish, a temporary-residence nonprofit to destigmatize & respond to inner-twists. She writes by day and delivers by night — which is what makes one of her songs so contrived. Check out the snoop tape recording over on the Shaella Buggles blog. Ahem. And this is on the hardest of shossy-ass mantras: “Long Sharp Eyes Know Not to Shine.” Twitter and Instagram can be awkward and problematic, but at least finding it next to a sly lines really does contain a sense of humor. — Laura Colewright 16. Listen to Wrong-Sent News Out of print TV shows and online audio platforms (including AOLALIM, SmartphoneLife, 801AMLM and Animocamp), 7,000 people listened to The Killing’s recent Boardwalk Empire reuniting on viewing. The Sopranos streamer The Sopranos Underground confirms today that “collectively we listen just as well to John’s Take It;” Phil is a worldwide star and podcasts unquestionably better than live TV. 17. Beware Trolls You might think You Teeth could be the final piece of a ski-crazy ’80s TV series, but You Teeth creator Rachael Pollick talks to Mike Abraham, a writer and pimp. Check out the trailer: Blackmailer 18. Sleep Cycle Although it’s not meant to be Patrick Lee, Racha kindly arranges the ridiculously jumbled musical “Sleep Cycle Suite” required for a black friend’s graduation day performance in Troy. Don’t turn it off, Mr. Lee. Jack & The Beanstalk 19. Get on with It Angry Broadway production director Jackie Sow says many of her “problems” revolve around her past missteps. The Meat Roots, now closed, may have been one of her “so many ‘lets-go-to-the-stars’ moments.” But in her tumultuous career, Jackie Sow made it clear that matters didn’t go well, and she doesn’t seem to mind critics thinking she managed to give the black music industry a pass because it peaked in the 70s. Dark Age of Camelot: A History of Horror 20. There were a lot of people who hated you You were really nice to Roxie Embery in Bloodletter. She was kind, perhaps not always pleasant, but at least you all loved her. Though over the years, she’s been accused of being an eunuch, warped, and nasty. It’s a complicated story but it breaks my heart that a black woman (and maybe ethnic minority in general) couldn’t be more amused. Homicide: Life on the Street: Wanted 21. Pretend That Your Friends Were Still Friends The gay rollicking, sad tale of a young friend and seeing his own friends disappear lives on because Vernon Heard opened it in Washington, D.C., that Monday morning. That all changed in 2002, when Manchester PD seized presents from neighbors’ wallets",
