        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000360",
        "text": "pieces of evidence established in court, as well as the work of someone who would still be able to find and debunk them. Yet, such a work remains very much a work in progress. It starts with the discovery of Blounts’ contradictory testimony, as well as a matching pair of Delphin armor plates. Chartered experts performing the original tests noted that each case was 99% identical, with good laboratory equipment allowing precise measurements. In October 1896, in an authorized run of the Inquiries at the Dora México Almas, however, we learned that that was not the case. In 1905, a considerable amount of evidence came in the form of patents covering Alcatel-Lucent’s ZX-95 research and development. The patent filing was by Nobel d’Agostinho et al. lawyer; Franz Lerner, professor of chemistry at Monsanto University in Madrid, in the opaqueness of a patent filing that his students routinely beat around and poked around in for hours despite many other rules of legal research. The three authors on the patent—Franz Lerner, Hendrik Blount, and Thierry Beeler—despised Lerner and used their extra years and hundreds of words of technical description to muddy the waters, and they were acquitted shortly after the report was leaked, doubtlessly promising more detail as the years went by. Two weeks after the report was published, Lerner told the journal Chemica Médica that he and his fellow lawyers had used multiple cases in which Alcatel-Lucent had used Zeiss Zeiss Optics, using patents for ZX-95, and Zeiss was discovering a new synthesis of blue-green metamorphism (which had been previously predicted by Erhard Schindler) using techniques of the period. Dr. Ferdinand Combes, the head of the Dora México Almas, recorded that he was very glad to be proven wrong. (His instructions to the civilian investigators taking part in the investigation were displayed prominently in my Internet search of his name.] The ZX-95 patents wrote in response to the Pau Top Pictures magazine article indicating that it “may yet be exploited as a research tool” and that it could be used in “a wide range of different gear during portable semiconductor work.” This would be quite the leap, especially in the context of the Peabody Award-winning DynaBeams, which featured the Zelenhooni factory in Mordecai, which was being refurbished for the project. However, we have several more competitors. Mimo, based in Montreal, was the first to pull out of its partnership with Alcatel-Lucent, concentrating its work in the desktop and development work, likely on alkaline phosphatase inhibition, before it withdrew from the partnership, which proved really rough for Alcatel to pull off in the first place. The Swedish company, at the time, seemed some 10% ahead of its fellow ZX-95 developers in the patent tracking and validation system, and we may even see them try the device sometime in the near future, much to the chagrin of any current employee of Alcatel, who in 1983 presumably resigned in protest at what he said were a series of issues in the patent. To many, the times behind the scenes in Mexican manufacturing do not quite fill the void of understanding this technological elite and their technology. As a result, there are many who have been offering story after story of their own inventions, someday perhaps to emerge as paradigm leads for creating new devices. Two decades or so ago, Dr. Jason Seymour-Matthew of Exeter, UK, was awarded the Peabody Award for his work in the fields of polymerizer production and an association with Bombardier Transportation, which helped him invent the pilot computer in the 1990s. Three years later, in 2001, Dr. Seymour-Matthew launched Molecular Theory Prize II: The Blounts patent, based on the encyclopaedia of synthetic biology, as a supplement to the Peabody Award for his hard work in the field and his collaborations with Wolfram Kulich. He was subsequently awarded the Global Prize, considered one of the 10 best prizes in science, internationally with other prizes from the Guggenheim Group and Saint-Louis researchers. The Carbon Dioxide at Burning Point What are the Sell-A-Petatoms of Mexico City’s forbidden explorers of space? My dream is to see yet another one seriously funded and excited, and to see what Dr. Seymour-Matthew is going on at General Fusion extending their ability to publish its content into publications throughout the world. I doubt that I will be the only one telling him so. UPDATE V: Forbes journalist Bill O’Reilly spoke to me last week on the phone from the scene in Mexico City. In the interview, he mentioned that he thinks Sibur, his own",
