        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000403",
        "text": "the town of Teidruck, about 200 kilometres from the Syrian border, is torn by weeklong purges. There are currently some 1,500 people traveling daily to Assad’s hometown of Latakia, which joined the rebel-held region at Christmas. On Saturday, the leadership of the opposition National Democratic Party (NDP) gave a platform that amounted to little more than a blanket condemnation of what the leaders called Assad’s “war crimes.” The spokeswoman for the organisation in Ramadi, Ghazan Pyatt, referred to the example of President Bashar Assad in his 17-month rule: “You behave as if they were your own people...and not nightmares. Talk could not be worse.” Although it may no longer have been a foregone conclusion that the current regime would fall after a historic victory in the 2002 Iraq war, the main priority of President Barack Obama’s administration remains to protect Syria. What are they to make of the growing number of airstrikes and shelling along Russia’s border? A military operation had been added to the ongoing Syrian civil war on Friday, following a Russian fighter jet in a crossing zone with Syria, which is now a major entry point for regime troops fleeing Aleppo. The Moscow Defense Ministry confirmed a Russian envoy had visited the truce zone in northern Latakia on Friday. Opposition sources close to the negotiations with the Syrian opposition say an offensive on Aleppo would only come at the edges of the plan: Lebanon and Lebanon’s militant Hezbollah would be the regime’s first targets. While their troops are still entrenched within the city, the pro-opposition fighters are preparing to launch a counteroffensive, through territory they have lost or captured, toward the northern city of Raqqa. As Assad’s forces retreat from northern Syria--which has now fallen to IS--the government and its allies are exploring how they could attack them more effectively. Those preparations have raised doubts within its ranks. Bashar al-Jaafari, a reformist war critic who had been in charge in the US-backed opposition, has since disowned the idea. “The Syrian opposition is the real solution to the popular uprisings,” Jaafari told a Russian news conference in Tehran. “We will be here talking about our efforts to protect the people and the people are anticipating that.” Jaafari rejected Moscow’s offer not to send planes to strike targets in Syria, arguing that the intervention against the Assad regime involved helping Russian troops to move well beyond Latakia. This is the second weekend in a row that eastern Aleppo has become a significant staging point for jihadist attacks. The city was previously hit by a coordinated assault that included Syrian dictator Bashar al-Assad’s forces, Russian-backed Shia militias and well-armed rebel militias. The first attack on western Aleppo was on Nov. 25, when at least 49 people were brutally slaughtered, in Salafist-inspired Anbar Province. And the city’s Merq Dam on Friday came under assault by the Syrian military’s near-peer affiliate HTS, which was given air support from Moscow. Late on Friday night, the rebels released an audio recording of 56 senior members of the Syrian army cutting a note in opposition Aleppo, pledging their allegiance to HTS. It signaled the beginnings of the third days of fighting between Russian, Iranian and HTS-backed forces on the outskirts of Aleppo. This article has been updated with additional comments from the Syrian Democratic Forces, which has been authorized to attack the Assad regime on Thursday, and with the second version of information provided by the National Democratic Party. Qualcomm is forecasting demand to grow by more than 4% quarter-on-quarter in 2013 and 4% annualized growth from Q4 2012 through Q4 2013, the company said. AMD, which is expected to probably cut 15,000 jobs last quarter, added another 2,000 PCs to the backlog year-over-year during the quarter. Qualcomm’s latest earnings report, which is likely to be the latest in a series of concerns to accompany anecdotal Q1 group-estimates, said the company now expects annual revenues to increase by 6% year-over-year, or $270M to $360M. All of Qualcomm’s devices are quad-core processors, with the company already moving to eight cores in Q1. Even with this, the firm will ship 920 million cellphones, or 10X more per quarter. Image Credit: Qualcomm Qualcomm is also expected to significantly increase revenues by substantially expanding its cloud operations and adding 500 new employees by the second quarter. It plans to add 35 new Cloud computing jobs and expand into new areas such as advisory, management services and data service for the enterprise. CEO Yandex Gartner says the sector left 88.25 million PC and conventional server units,",
