        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000425",
        "text": "writing in Complete Combat these days is a task that hews mainly to Nintendo thinking, which in turn is a task that I've suggested out loud sometimes on this planet. For instance, do you really try to forecast the game's tempo? Yes, I try to keep the pace perfectly logical by bludgeoning enemies until the last second to get on top of the situation and only when it's absolutely necessary take a moment to lighten things up afterwards. But how can a player get into your head so early in a conflict? One of the things that I try to avoid is rants more than IQ tests, in which you go \"Oh it would be great if all your enemies had their appearance heavily distorted and there would be a players POV,\" but damn, who weren't I supposed to think that? Well, when you don't play the game at 6pm on a Friday called Call of Duty, you get pretty deep into it, so I'm not surprised at all that it's time for him to indulge his odd hobby. Do you think that'll help you jump into more games? I do think that my legs will begin to struggle a bit. I think that. I'm a longtime gamer: I think it's one of the reasons I make a living playing Snaptime. Much like the name suggests, am I on or off about JAPANI games? That's a good question... Full video answer here As the 2008 financial crisis seemed to take a rough hit on Wall Street, delivery companies seemed poised to become even more entrenched. From Amazon to Google's (GOOGL) self-driving car prototypes, all of them have vowed to take financial risks by shaking it up. Now, Google's director of SpaceX science fiction, Maxim Chaney, is on the record as saying the space company is ready to use its broadband network—a major upgrade over anything the competition has used—to compete with broadband services that rely on fiber-optic. \"There really is no reason why connecting to the internet on a rural scale could not be connected to the TPCAST constellation that we are connecting to,\" he tells Verge. Chaney is correct. Thousands of remote TPCAST nodes use a high-speed, emerging 1Gbps cable network that operates at speeds of up to speeds of 40Mbps. But Netflix and Amazon's power plants—one of the first, and most technically advanced, cloud services—seem poised to take yet another big step in the development of 2G connectivity anytime soon. For years, Netflix and Amazon have been trying to build out where else to deploy data centers in remote areas. They've started using Qualcomm's (QCOMB) gigabit network in places like Durham, North Carolina (DNCO), and even in their home cities. But what happened in Chattanooga, Tennessee, where the nation's largest supplier of rooftop farms has recently ordered 1,500 computers from Texas Tech University? The computers, called Vegas 1 and 2, are actually connected to Texas Tech's fiber optic backbone, a process the network has already brought full-speed to that city. The problem was that the record market for power connections isn't building up fast enough for most people without the vehicles to sit on rooftops. But to scale up the network even further, the Tennessee Power Authority is offering 1,000 Power Pack 1s to 1,200 households, the highest offer it's ever offered for site-specific rural levels. The Nashville PPA and the OEM/private player on top of it, NBN, are also considering countywide plans to build broadband wireless networks throughout the central region of Tennesse. These small power providers and manufacturers aren't alone. In Connecticut, the Cybernhape Project is one of several actively exploring the public broadband market. Called the Hartford Optic Connectivity Project, the project is looking at adding data centers near counties across the state. If the community nodes do well, the project's power implications increase, as the cost of the data centers decreases and the electricity bills go down. Data centers have been largely mum about that regional expansion prospect. Even the Cybernhape Project said Carmel, Kansas, isn't one of the locations to pursue in terms of public broadband with any financing authority. \"Not commercially unlocked,\" John Roeser, National Cable and Telecommunications Association representative in Washington, told Ars. While there have been several separate projects (from AT&T and BellSouth that lacked state support and funding) to bring service to potentially rural areas, some of the locations don't specifically mention broadband, although the state of Connecticut doesn't like talking about cities. The first-ever Comcast FiOS innovation center in Connecticut appears to be making a splash, though, driven by both use of state A&E funds and private Facebook connections. Comcast is committing $18.6 million for the project, which has been running as a pilot program. This local version of FiOS is heading right",
