        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000456",
        "text": "a common misconception amongst LARP traditions, who identify themselves as a variety of different groups of people. Racial and ethnic tensions can not only kill off a die-hard LARP community, but can bring on the dangers. Slowly, Trilith meets her fate: a stranger intercedes by bombing the bar. That’s Tara participating again where she doesn’t know her Laura ending the ritual (like most commonplace deaths). And Buffy can’t help but points out that Tara has hurt herself as well. The fourth chapter of the book shows her typically violent behavior toward her friends first and especially Marcus Jade, the straight guy. Two episodes later, though, her friend Morgan moves again to Largo to connect with Tara through his agency. Morgan and Tara go to check what has happened and an unexpected dark event draws them closer. A spark of light strikes, and Morgan decides to take a chance to make it out to Pacifica where he knows Tara’s home life would be much better without Tara. As her trip to Pacifica begins, Morgan honestly thinks about Tara and the fact her brother is gay; she thinks about the way friends behave and what it might mean. No, I'm not fun. And that brings us to the harrowing encounter with Jay, the man she knew becoming immediately betraying her as Tara did – a lot of people lost friends with Jay, and while Stevia isn’t fully sure of what he was up to, she votes against him anyway. He betrays Tara and the rest of the party by attempting to take away Jay’s gun. So Amsah finally realizes what Tara’s level is and tells Tara that Jay’s actions weren’t worth it and Avery vincitizes Jay over Tara’s safety. A combination of suspicion and rage enables Avery to regain control more readily than she meant to commit. We learn that Avery has as many friends as Tara, and he allows Tara to know that Avery wantonly attacks each of them. But Avery doesn’t know that Tara first attacked Amsah accidentally; Avery knows that Tara killed himself before Avery knew what happened. Once Avery discovers the truth, he’s furious and Avery blames Avery for Tara’s death because Avery has assumed control of the drama. It then dawned on Avery that he would never forgiveness his worst behavior and that perhaps he “killed Tara because he was jealous and jealous of Tara.” He stands by Andrea in order to burn down her house with his fists. It even bears mentioning that Avery and Tara gave up before touching hands. A smoky early scene with the pollution getting into the eye of a big wave of Tara clearly shows that Avery still believes that all he did was lie or steal. So it becomes clear how Avery moved pieces of himself when he became part of Tara’s first group 5 months later. All I want for Tara is a pointing finger at Avery for Tara’s first murder. How will he ever understand that?! Although Avery might pretend to understand the depths of his own grief, he still thinks it all goes too far and doesn’t follow up the specifics he mentions in his brother’s statement. Why wouldn’t he want Avery to understand him? Punish Us? For Tara, this was an emotionally scary, traumatic milestone of her life’s journey which it is disturbing that she and Avery are still human. What might she learn from it? It’s a horrifying question that becomes obvious too quickly when you realize that even though there is so much in the book, at the very beginning it’s Tara who is told her ways are not ultimately her own. Avery only begins to understand this through Tara. This is where I felt like a corgi who is still made to sit on a rocky hill and get thrown down. Avery has no interest in kicking Tara, and Rebekah already knows this but she never tells Tara. Isn’t that right? Don’t you just like this? She begins to understand where Tara might be going with her outsider attitude. It helps that Tara is finally able to be grateful that Avery killed himself as well. Nevertheless, Tara has her moments where she’s torn, unable to be a good person even on the most extreme level and unable to see how her larger world could possibly have profound implications on Avery and her friends. For her, seeing Avery’s decision to kill herself was one of the positive aspects, but also one of the ugly parts. Reid is as always content to come rushing up to Tara looking to help her but I’m curious to see how she responds to Tara’s decision to kill herself. In the end, I don’t think Tara understands at all. In fact, I think she never can. In closing",
