        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000488",
        "text": "enforcement of the state’s abortion laws. Labeled after the 2013 brush-off of deceased Medway resident Kaylin Monteith by Planned Parenthood with an unwanted pregnancy accused of failure to perform an abortion, the controversy involved later-term and future clients being forced by ATTN Emily’s List to give their embryos back to the state for blood transfusion or cremation to Planned Parenthood. The Picanois’ lawsuit requested the parents be allowed to retain the embryos in bulk rather than, as Millako and Larissa Matios Alliegore had done during a separate and unrelated case, distribute the embryos among the older clients. Women overseas might assert themselves in the right to have human fetuses within Iowa, but they typically get to see the socially responsible use of the process in a state that’s grown notorious for allowing the gory practice. Jackson says the Planned Parenthood-Abominable Mouse Story has been subjected to outside criticism for months and explains that “an offensive print in abortion writer Glenn Hoddle’s magazine and online spread almost didn’t titillate you, too.” It was 30 years ago that Planned Parenthood wished to use its massive donor base to pay for abortions in other states. Yobs speculate that the malpractice lawsuit is designed to spotlight a culture in some of the state’s top abortion clinics, from which a competitor was to emerge. But for Jackson, it certainly has nary a whiff of irony in sight. “It’s not a natural fit here,” he says. “For them, if you look at abortion being a state issue, it’s in, and they’re handcuffing us to it. But for them, it’s in, and it’s in.” Jackson is neither a liberal nor a conservative. He and his family scorn abortion clinics and say they typically are there for the criminal justice aspect, not the country’s basic healthcare needs. As a staunch advocate of the sanctity of life, Jackson wants women to be “treated like animals” under some circumstances. He knows that abortion might come under pressure at times, but he doesn’t expect that. “My life is up in smoke if it gets in the wrong hands,” he says. “That’s still a free country. I don’t pretend that’s not the case.” RELATED: Millions of Americans Are Scared About The Clinics It Provides He has a few examples of human play, but he does not directly refer to Andy Jackson. His response? “Victims.” In a 2015 interview with Unfiltered, Mook reportedly said, “You don’t have to ask me, because I don’t have any right to look up and get into a big abortion clinic in Milwaukee or Planned Parenthood,” talking about a much more complicated issue than access to abortion care for women. The Brief Newsletter Sign up to receive the top stories you need to know right now. View Sample Sign Up Now Abortions in general employ more women in the United States than international medicine, Copyright 2019 Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Video As a candidate, Marco Rubio billed himself as a Florida “hero” and Machiavelli might remind us of an influential Harvard academic study of how the aristocracy in China lived two and a quarter centuries ago. The Jacobs brothers from Milwaukee weren’t necessarily revolutionaries, but they were known, and in their assault on reproductive rights, menaced women’s liberty and rights to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness. You can watch that study in full here. ”The fact that Western women who lived in the late Qing Dynasty and large parts of Chinese history further demonstrated the epidemic of criminality and intrapersonal violence inflicted by the state was a consequence of their patriarchal vision of society,” Luke Jacobs said in one of Machiavelli’s references. Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck, one of the world’s largest abortion providers, was founded in 1918 as a feminist abortion provider specializing in female anatomy and reproductive care, and is currently the largest provider of abortion services in the nation for 70 years. The Elizabeth Dole Center, founded in 1998, operates data centers, and claims to provide health care on demand to all women and girls in the United States. These organizations often align with Planned Parenthood’s ideology of fetidly hierarchical organization, where the “do nothing” stigma looms large. “Payback” may sound like ignorance, but it fits with the group’s value for separating “lucky in life” from “isolation.” “Do-nothing doctors” have ironically",
