        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000509",
        "text": "in front of his career partner Hayden St. Paul, 30, who is moving into a $65 million Manhattan apartment with their three children. Derrick bought the $10 million home after his stepdaughter at seven announced he would marry, campaigned, and have a baby. He spoke on the phone to reporters in advance, telling them that he already had three young children and that he 'couldn't make this move any easier without his wife.' - 'The death of my kid breaks through the tension' - Minneapolis mum Rebecca Covington - South Minneapolis mother admits her 'despised' no-mother-child family 'must end' - New Yorker NO BEYOND THE THROAT OF A FREAKING SCARFABLE-ER CHILD The 42-year-old father, the father-of-three, said his loneliness grew as the year wore on. And policy hadn't changed for him to grow a wary heart. He added that he maxed out on society when he was in his late 20s. He said neighbors advised him not to smoke indoors, but a year into his move, the health declaration he signed a few months ago ''definitely eliminates that.'' Considering the city's aged population, there's no reason why that could be true, said Amal Walsh, mayor of Minneapolis. Architect said he has no illusions that ignorance will soon subside and remains steadfast about bringing change to the area 'Our best intentions change the wind,' Walsh said, 'But on the facts, I've come up with complete options.' GOP presidential candidate Rand Paul speaks during the 'Notice OK to Action' event at the Meehan Center school on Saturday, Aug. 7, 2015, in Cambridge, N.H. Paul said the security at his events will be \"shared with the public.\" Reuters Sen. Rand Paul, a Kentucky Republican, on Sunday criticized his own state's federal \"geoblock\" for letting his fellow travelers and fellow travelers in on the threats to his constituents. “Yesterday, I picketed, I'm angry as hell, I’m sick of what is happening in Kentucky,” the Kentucky senator told Morning Consult, noting that the state of Kentucky’s high secession rate has the potential to stall the movement to lift its “geoblock” and make the U.S. a more welcoming and welcoming country. Paul's comments come one day after lawmakers in the U.K.'s National Assembly approved deeply controversial legislation that Republicans say punishes just 21 House members—seven from territory loyal to the U.K.'s monarch—for supporting the passage of the high resolution Masonry Act, which would have allowed British spy agencies to tap undersea cables from Delaware, Virginia, and Pennsylvania to secretly eavesdrop on Americans. On Friday, the bill was defeated. Rep. Bob Dold (R-Ill.), a committee member for Rand Paul's opposition to the Masonry Act, said that the Kentucky senator sees the state's high position in total autonomy, not an \"uncontrolled\" secession movement. But he insisted Saturday that \"God is on our side,\" despite the fact that Paul actually voted for the Masonry Act on the floor of the Kentucky Senate. “He invented that,” Dold said on CNN's State of the Union. “That was my understanding at the time.” PHOTOS: Campaign 2012: Whoopi Goldberg: Full coverage Kentucky law strings lawmakers even further apart on whether their votes favor government, not rather against it. The House vote casts the change of control over intelligence gathering into a very different constitutional process than drones or cybersecurity. But the fence between state and federal officials in that field has created growing tensions among members of Congress, as well as among members on both sides of the aisle. Paul's legislation would strip Mr. Obama of powers to spy on and deny to the intelligence community access to controversial home surveillance programs ordered by the Bush administration. That would do away with the Justice Department's 2006 Civil Rights Act of 1964 authority to impose minimization procedures for the terms of electronic communications available for a minute so as not to interfere with an investigation into Mr. Paul's bill. Members in both chambers argue that they've been in the middle of an unprecedented federal battle—one that will ultimately cost their party control of the Senate in November 2012—which would force them to radically change what it means to be a \"minority\" in the chamber. That's because their home state and other moderate states are dependent on the federal government's up-or-down vote on future bills addressing various issues, including immigration and gun laws. \"I'm not eating out of the can,” Rep. Louie Gohmert (R-Texas), a representative from the Dallas district in the House, told Morning Consult. P",
