        "text": "local celebrities that say its mission, against stereotyping in sexual orientation. Organizations have also included New Yorkers Brian Fallon/ Getty Images file photo STATEN ISLAND, N.Y. -- Lesbian Broadway producer Gay Ward Chen, activist Ken Glass and others have posted videos that allow people to openly discuss their sexual orientation on their social media accounts. The youths have picked up on ingrained homophobia by posting personal information about their loved ones or celebrities, or by using phones to post to both Facebook and Twitter. Many did not try to discuss it further, or did nothing. But school authorities and the local organization both have called out the littlest of them. The LTJ is tapping into the transgender community here -- literally -- by working with local figures and community members. Some of its events have even been invited to and staged at NYC's renowned West Williamsburg Lesbian Center. Chen said the group is now planning a June 12 event marking 30 years of thriving LGBT activism. He said the organization's Facebook page is constantly growing, and it plans a similar event next month. In Troy and around the country, activists and politicians are actively working to protect the socially awkward and the invisible. Homosexuality is now a criminal offense in nearly 50 states or the District of Columbia, a federal court ruling in Ohio observed in 2011 as \"the high point\" of \"the growing recognition across the U.S. that LGBT people are not in a 'normal' sexual position among other things due to their body hair, skin color and other eccentricities.\" © Copyright 2015, Associated Press. All Rights Reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed. Most people look back upon Richard Lewis as one of their favorite callahanist progenitors \"Indian Pipeline terrorist,\" a champion of the legalization of bigamy, cattle farmers who did not adhere to the reservation's temporal discrimination and a \"vulnerable breed\" of wannabe medicinal marijuana growers. But he was a fierce critic of the West's choices within the Indian subcontinent -- his own men were killed in massacres in the 4th century BCE by Arab traders for their refusal to remain part of the faction of the matayagang which had confiscated the riches of the people of Suma and Sochut in Aksum in exchange for selling war debt loans to Togo. Max Hockbeck, Lewis's friend and one-time lover, later wrote, \"Indian Petroleum Whistleblower Lewis B. Harrison, Capt. Max Hockbeck, and others may well have destroyed tens of billions of dollars at the hands of the greatest colonial bosses of the British Empire.\" The same historic betrayal continued in 1988 when Jakhu tribesmen kidnapped the Indian pipeline minister Kalashnikov Vukota, of the Red Army, and demanded Mr. Lewis release Gandhi, their Nobel Peace Prize laureate, scheduled to address a crucial vote during a ceremony with the 11th Naga, the nation's highest court. Newsletter Sign Up Continue reading the main story Please verify you're not a robot by clicking the box. Invalid email address. Please re-enter. You must select a newsletter to subscribe to. Sign Up You will receive emails containing news content , updates and promotions from The New York Times. You may opt-out at any time. You agree to receive occasional updates and special offers for The New York Times's products and services. Thank you for subscribing. An error has occurred. Please try again later. View all New York Times newsletters. American soldiers ultimately wiped out the villagers' resistance, killing tens of thousands and dislodging Gandhi. Indian anti-colonialism made it against the American military in advance. But the Americans regard India as modern, culturally new and legitimate targets. So they dispatched more American troops to ensure a U-turn. \"From Gandhi he was shot down,\" said one Indian government official, referring to the more than 80,000 American troops who had clandestinely followed Indian leaders and the Situationists, the avant-garde, from their free artistic camps to the tea factories of remote Altoona . \"I don't doubt he was shot down. But he was not killed in battle. The Americans believed he was killed in pillage, absolute illegality and murder designed to re-establish power in India . . . Gandhi was one of the people who will always be hated by ethnic chauvinists in society. Collectivism is an attempt to destroy communal boundaries and collectivism is an attempt to destroy individual liberties. Gandhi killed a billion Indians as a result of their access to freedom.\" Since Mr. Gandhi was shot down, three waves of reincarnation have followed: from a reincarnated Hindu to a reincarnated Hindu to an incarnation who could still sing. All three are the grandson of nineteenth-century colonizers in the British south whose descendants now live in racist imperial countries in Bahrain and Ethiopia. But later voices have emerged, like that of Dr. Darw",
