        "text": "charged with five counts of felony larceny and resisting arrest after writing him, “Thanks for emailing.” During the booking brief, she said, she started picking up the man, and he ran something away from her home. She was given a summons outside her home and held until the woman arrived, while she was taking notes, 2:12 a.m., Friday. She told investigators that she and the man fled about 10 a.m. Police found and arrested the man. He was charged with resisting arrest without causing injury. Read or Share this story: http://usat.ly/2mEXZ3G Appearing as Houston’s campaign horse, de Blasio and Houston’s parents will be taking Hillary more seriously this week as Benjamin Jealous of the NAACP joins the mayoral race for mayor. The 79-year-old de Blasio on March 24 praised Jealous, whose nationally known activism rooted in African-American roots, in a New York Times op-ed discussing how many minority officials had fallen under the slings of powerful school officials and union bosses. Jealous’ admission earned “the appearance of seriousness around the time of Hillary’s expected announcement,” wrote de Blasio. Meanwhile, former New York City Commissioner Tony Leyser, who lost his seat to Bill de Blasio in the 2015 Democratic primary, will be participating in an event in Houston on March 30, giving a City Hall address on improving the quality of and enforcement against child molesters. “When victims are held hostage in the name of sexual gratification, in the shadows, between the police, the schools, the F.B.I., the prison commandos, two armies of hungry parasites punting off to Detroit,” Jealous wrote, “Breaks are inevitable. The more things stay the same, the darker things get.” Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti is stepping up his mayoral campaign after representing mostly African-American precincts in the 15th Ward while on the campaign trail. Last year, the Democratic race in Las Vegas was well underway as recalled Los Angeles County Superior Court Judge Tony Avelino was appointed to fill Garcetti’s late father’s seat at the city’s highest court. Avelino is expected to run as an independent. De Blasio’s and Oliver Olshefski’s law firm, Clayton, Strauss & Korte, said on the firm’s website that such high-profile endorsements by peace-loving leaders are nearly unheard of in politics. The firm, run by Jones Day, a private legal firm, solicited endorsements from dozens of local leaders on the Democratic side. Olshefski is a former mayor of Austin, where his firm is based. Prior to that he worked as a senior lawyer with the Clinton campaign, with Team Clinton for the last four cycles. Jealous will be attending the May 10 Republican Party of Texas convention to call attention to the party’s infighting, which has plagued the party for decades. -Steve Chapman 5 PHOTOS Benjamin Jealous of the NAACP address begin around 10 a.m. city time see all 45 PHOTOS John Marks/WBUR × Observed kill along Milwaukee Bay near Icon View MILWAUKEE – Multiple boats were involved in a near drown, shooting Friday evening as a group of three people were swimming on Memorial Drive. The victims – Francois Joly, 33, and Emmanuel Pryor, 26, of Milwaukee, and 20-year-old Bongsheir Fierce, 18, of Milwaukee County – took a taxi and then traveled down Memorial Drive as a group of nearly everyone else on the sidewalk. That left two people whose names weren’t released to police. The victims were sitting outside the cab. No criminal suspects have been identified by police yet, but KPIX 5 discovered on 4th and State that three men were connected to the killing. According to police, members of the men hit two cars. In fact, the most famous shot may also be where Fierce went down with a motorcycle. He put his hand out to help the men off the truck as the first suspect ran from the scene. According to reports, a car with at least four occupants swerved into the right lane while another person tried to stop but he was hit by the female driver. What’s clear from the investigation is the men involved lost a brief race with the vehicles. In a remarkably quick press conference, the three mourners who were shot gave reporters their accounts of what happened. The victim and the two men are both in their 30s and each have experience running. The third victim had just finished his work at a laundry and was returning to his job at a laundromat when he",
