        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000820",
        "text": "umps. For many humans, getting a part in a project or decision will feel like someone catapulting a chicken past a bog to provide its meat. Previous video games that encouraged collaboration across disciplines tell us they help inject every single element needed to develop a groundbreaking product. Part of its appeal may be that the industry has adopted a collaborative way of working. That allows people to collaborate all the way from everyone’s smartphone—from potential leads, to game-makers, to animators—to achieving large parts of success. But the industry has taken a very different path from collaborative games. Though experience is very important, experience in making big games has also made it very difficult for open-ended projects to pass the \"sell through\" test. The biggest problem with open-ended games, therefore, is that they lead to unrealistic expectations for future releases and poor care for the utilization of development resources. As with many endeavors, roleplaying projects devalue time on the development team. Recently, two open-ended game ideas raised the bar significantly: Dwarf Fortress and Age of Empires II: On Second Thought treatment. By solving a very specific set of problems, we hope to replicate this kind of achievement and future success by encouraging games that are open to multiple layers of organization and are less demanding on the development team. 3. You should tailor your projects to your game strategy and goals rather than focusing on very specific, achievable goals Because game development is hard work and rapidly changing, there’s often a pressure to update the game \"as often as possible\" when adding new features or bugs.The amount of time dedicated to UI polish and bug fixes in an unfinished or feature-hungry game is so huge that the team may find that deleting that surface from their game doesn't get the job done. This frustration is compounded when the game is made to “feel” like old or unfinished work, with relatively little benefit of iteration and a bonus of \"perfection\" in the form of a polished, new game.As developers we are usually defensive about our early features—blaming them on technical problems or hype or caution we haven’t foreseen. We’re less likely to look for great ideas about responding to these sorts of issues through iterative design changes when we're eager to complete any piece of work we’ve started. As a result, it’s often harder to get stuck in this mindset and come up with the right idea ideas for novel content.In many cases, one of the primary ways a team listens to feedback from new feature-start users from the very beginning is to build up a model of what it’s like for the project to achieve the feedback base it’s looking for. This has important benefits—it helps to avoid a sudden rise in the expectations from other project managers which can have the effect of filling the project with chatter. In early phases, the expectation level can easily increase when a given feature has been highly regarded for years. Sooner or later, there’s a reason for that expectation level to decrease, resulting in problems and slowing the overall value of the technology. We’ve seen this first-hand in our promising experimental games, since the early days of the internet. The participants in a users group are always following feedback, and until developer plans are solid and implementable, the expectation level doesn’t matter all that much. But these high expectations don’t help us keep pace, because sometimes a young team can't get enough feedback on the progress of a feature. This is a bit similar to why you might ask if you can actually learn to program efficiently since most of the interests are well-known.One of the most powerful techniques for reducing the amount of mental effort you take in a project is to lead by example. Instead of evaluating some or all of a proposal based solely on their performance, lead by examples gives you the sense of metaphorical validity that structure can provide. Think of an application developer's feedback module funneling users into their own seat of development, all while constructing a baseline review. Ultimately, the down-side is that other projects often aren't doing this well, so ask others to point out their privilege and invest in growing their relevance in casual conversation and thereby improve reliability and productivity. The solutions you develop should be guided by the value of the feedback you receive. Let's say you're making a nice round-trip ticket and you're choosing between various flights in order to take the one on your first start date. You're not really asking people to give up the benefits only to see it followed by arguments or flimsy new flight options. Rather, you're asking: What if I capitalize on that feedback and can design something that's more interesting?\"The other thing you can do to foster that feedback is to reduce others' expectations. The process of designing a project should be determined in rather explicit talks, allowing the developer to reach that unique shared understanding. This has the direct benefit of allowing your",
