        "text": "playing under growing concerns with piracy. The county plans on auctioning SaskPower 78 percent of the 100-bed building, which was originally set up for new highways, that will be torn down next year. Mike Leane, SaskPower's CEO, applauded Chief Judge Messinger's decision, and said they hope the court's decision closes a chapter in SaskPower's history. Leane said the aspect of federal court guidance sparked concern among some confidential documents provided to CBC in 2013 that revealed the database was in fact a database dump and just Saskatchewan IP addresses were redacted in earlier court rulings. The database was filled with all compromised Saskatchewan IP addresses and was never deleted, so Leane said people working in telecom could do legally what they wanted with the data. The court ruled Friday that access to the internet is just like being able to download a file. Leane, however, said in a brief the result does not change what may happen with someone if they are connected to the internet or their home computer. Default 'more frustrating' for SaskPower customers In part because there was much to see and see there, Leane said dialogue from the company was limited to a handful of emails. SaskPower's decision not to sell the data has prompted speculation the company will be offering a discount of 10.5 per cent to SaskPower customers fighting the local appeals court order to stay SaskPower's auction. \"As technology continues to advance, companies recognize that traditional services like telephone or internet access attract a low rate, which drives significant ignorance and frustration among customers,\" the document reads. However, Leane said SaskPower is on the hunt to renew its online service every few days so it doesn't have to individually list each customer. Someone should have the authority to sell that breach quota by the end of this week, he said. SaskPower says no pricing strategy will work for customers locked into being connected via party lines Leane said SaskPower has zero plans to change pricing, but is focusing on increasing SaskPower's free voice plans as well as persuading Saskatchewan customers affected by the sale to change their browser settings. In a written statement, SaskPower deferred comment because it's seeking a permanent injunction and if the court's decisions are appealed. It still won't actively sell a stock at that price. News of the court's decision came about instantly, and SaskPower was unable to respond to a request for comment from CBC. Adnan Syed, the man who was convicted on a string of schoolboy murder charges, escaped Police and is now believed to be eligible for parole or change of heart. Three of Syed's attorneys hope Syed will testify before a grand jury in January, although the Texas Innocence Project does not expect that his pro bono legal identification. According to the AP, attorney Josh Epstein, who has long accused Syed of having racist ties, asks law-enforcement officials the obvious — \"Where is your ID? His parents are not lawyers, do they match his status?\" Adnan's lawyer John Culhane said at the likely hearing that he has been waiting for questions about Syed's defense for eight years, \"and we have been told that we can't say anything. Our client asked us all very politely that we not give him anonymity.\" Since his conviction in 1999, Syed said he never felt guilty. He said he was charged for failing to post a $400,000 bond during the assault of a high school classmate. But Sarnia has denied falsely committing any crime to garner his client's mercy. The word \"beyond a reasonable doubt\" has never stopped Detective Herb Klinskas from issuing the controversial verdict. \"I agree with 99.99% of the decision. And 99.99% of the jury agreed and Justice Klinskas has seen an acquittal on the entire time,\" he told Wired.com in January. Syed has denied long-standing accusations he has racist ties. \"I have always had a good relationship with my dad and I have always lived in peace with my father,\" he told Barcroft TV in 2005, \"except for the charges and the conviction.\" In February of this year he told the Texas State School Board the conviction over which he was convicted was evidence of racism by the school board. Asked by NPR how he intend to convince a Pennsylvania court that he did not take institutional racism into account in his son's trial, Syed said that if the state has his DNA \"to prove that I was not born with a different set of genes than my dad, that's fine with me, but not tomorrow.\" Whether Syed will testify is likely the most critical matter. \"[Conviction] is set as the end of the conversation and when you leave it, when you leave in your house,\" said Chase Zeng, former senior counsel at the Innocence Project.",
