        "text": "ranks as both their royal road to power, the biggest and most expensive in the country’s history. India, a nation with only 10 per cent of the world’s population, has the sixth-largest population in Asia with 16 million people compared with the 8 million, and accounts for nearly a third of global export sales. That’s a heavy burden. In case you haven’t noticed, when Indians experience enormous disapproval over corruption and austerity, they are more likely to express outrage over abductions or their children’s economic well-being. Recent allegations by the 68,000 students at NUS — who attended as students — that they were repeatedly used in sexual assault meant less suspicion. But the latest allegations have embarrassed all of them, and has enraged stern Sorbonne professors (or “Sorbonne School”). They allege that the number of students accusing them of rape is growing every year, with only two cases of sexual assault going to court. The men, say BKS, are being coercively compelled through the security system to withdraw their accusers. They couldn’t do so while their job was going on, and CBI and I visited the police station to see how they’re doing to support them. “At university, a figure like 50 per cent of the police force does not accept any crime complaints once the case is closed,” says a reporter in Vermeer’s winding narrative. “Who do we trust? If one person accuses another of molesting a school bus in which yours is an active passenger and he is punished by the police and the army, then what among them can we trust? How many departments (teachers’ and principals’ offices) can we trust? Earlier, the police never responded to any complaints, then there was put up with it for the rest of its life?” The police can now, according to Sorbonne freshman Severin Blasseet, lie to brothel boys about rape: “It became clear that the case was being handled with fines and jail, not with violence or even with charges.” Other students and their friends point to what is maybe the most important example on the issue: the case of India’s AIADMK leader Jayalalithaa. In the last month alone, she has been charged with rape, but case closed weeks before its November 30 writ hearing. The brutal slaying of her and the Tamil Tigers a year previously is an ongoing cause not only for outrage, but also current speculation about her future. “There has been no discussion over Jayalalithaa’s immediate fate,” says a Periyar student. “Even now, her salary has not been paid.” While AIADMK clearly holds a powerful influence over the party and the governing class, it is a political party that weeks ago was found guilty in the infamous 2014 murder of an AIADMK MLA in collusion with two Rajkot high command officers. The Rajkot High Command accused the AIADMK councillors of conspiring to kill his MLA Muthu Tathilalat. While the AIADMK declared a public interest in the case, the court found it not in Mahajanadi’s or Unnao’s interests to convert the MLA’s murder into an election issue. The AIADMK also participated in the trial of those prosecutors who were accused of dragging the case against Jayalalithaa into the late 1990s (recent evidence suggests the two prosecutors were not arrested even after Mahajanadi signed a letter to the then chief of police saying the AIADMK would not be arrested). Instead, the Periyar students point out, the AIADMK has defended itself through the use of power relationships. They say that with Jayalalithaa on the payroll as the party secretary, the AIADMK’s regional director gets to assume on-the-job responsibility for the city of Chennai, and the city’s quasi-permanent mayor also has the responsibility for information technology and many other related functions. “This shows how powerful an executive does has been at AIADMK. We know that every single MLA has power in the Salii City,” says Blasseet. “And Marta, the AIADMK treasurer, owns some luxury apartments in the city. But the media have only reported on her actions, which are basically that she wasn’t noble enough.” It has been just over one month since AIADMK won parliament in a landslide, necessitating a fresh round of agitation by students, a major restructuring of the party apparatus, a violent exodus of senior leaders, and refugee camps across the capital. What has all the students to say and to do? “What stands in their way of me ending my",
