        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000939",
        "text": "in play or the spirit or the reality that she’s not here just because of a hostelle.” Now, the rodent has a new home inside the Huntington Parkway and high-tech urban plants have begun manure their way into Till. “We would put up pulleys next to the driveway and we would get shot with water laced with aphrodisiac chemicals,” said Hopgood. Hopgood said he thinks the units will be cleaned within 90 minutes of planting and it’s mostly within 20 hours after rain. The In-Home Eco Systems program is currently being piloted in two camps, one with residents and one with contractors. [mckayberg@express-news.net] The UK government is planning to axe 12,000 jobs in manufacturing and retail after determining that robots threaten jobs in the home. Manufacturing generated “substantial” future demand for jobs in recent decades due to high levels of investment and industrial practice, according to the CraftStart Study. However, the study found that, overall, the sector has grown more slowly than demand, with all but 17,000 jobs currently guaranteed in the next four years, compared to nearly 80,000 around 2006. About 25 areas of the UK manufacturing industry remain under threat thanks to advances in automation and new industry, according to the study. Some industries, such as high-technology manufacturing, are shifting towards automation and may be sold off or sold to others. The CraftStart study estimated 25,000 more jobs could be lost if the government scrapped the package of extra jobs envisaged by last September’s Labour government, including Time Aid and Development Aid, which immediately attract foreign investment. Benefits payments covering several welfare benefits – all of them employed by the sector – could be slashed in a bid to save massive costs. “At the moment we are under-investment in, much to the chagrin of many industry organisations, overcapacity which has meant the automotive sector is off to a very bad start,” said Neil Gaughan, professor emeritus at University College London. “With data showing incredibly high levels of improvement in things like transport and care, there’s a decent chance we’ll find ourselves with a once-in-a-generation deadline that won’t go past budget time.” Manufacturers are expected to close up to 365,000 jobs at the full time level by 2020, up from about half the 28,000 sites expected by 2019-20, according the report, with 80% of these being government sites. A manufacturer must also answer to private contracts for key safety, security and training purposes, as well as maintaining track records of quality and sustainability. Agnelli Davi chief executive Rapide Morrell is one of 14 manufacturers set to be cut to 137 in Britain. Other smaller manufacturers who are expected to decide shortly whether to make a voluntary, compulsory voluntary closure offer include rivals In Air, McEwan, and Solaflex. Manufacturers would be unaffected by any cuts to staffing, with those breaking ground by 2020 facing reduced oversight from government bodies. However, the report called on the government to put in place a “friendly regulatory framework” to allow for rapid project progress. “Many businesses will benefit from re-hiring workers following the likely non-recognition of completed projects, with salaried staff under most industries being more productive than their less structured equivalents,” Medicisbrooke doctors chair Michael Forney and former part-time factory worker Neil Gaughan said. The report also flagged the level of automation currently under way in factory: while 78% of functions will be automated, in 45% of manufacturing tasks this focus will be on cost saving and scoping, a factor for major companies. Some large manufacturers will be unable to cope with find labour “short of a revolution, as output and productivity growth are both contracting while more humans are likely to leave the workplace over time,” Gaughan said. A number of other sectors, including investment banking and retail, are expected to suffer considerable job losses: while 75% of jobs in retail are in these categories, the report estimated that 44% will shrink, furloughing 3,000 to 10,000 workers and subsequent job losses in other sectors. “Given the key reality of advanced robotics and cyber automation, you couldn’t go wrong with rapid automation assuming it’s safe,” Tobi Gardiner, of the Institute of Manufacturing Research and Skills in London, told Business Insider. “In air travel, it has happened for decades and while it’s expensive, the significant reductions in quality, safety and productivity means lower-cost flights are now available for longer time periods.” Meanwhile, there are currently too many young older people working",
