        "id": "owt-owt_ar_base-000947",
        "text": "of the most successful recipes in the history of chemistry' Recipe Collection Get the biggest daily stories by email Subscribe Thank you for subscribing See our privacy notice Could not subscribe, try again later Invalid Email Thousands of Irish people have said they are “worried” after a cardboard cut-out of former President Jimmy Carter appeared in the streets on the frontier east of Dublin. Three men (pictured) and a dog were left with a cardboard cut-out of the former US president. A Facebook friend of the man written on the cardboard believed to be Sonny Carter was a “sensitive individual”. Discussion on the background behind the cardboard cut-out appears to have included the famous slogan: “Two warriors for justice and equality.” The cardboard cut-out appears to have appeared in Kenny’s Cafe near Dublin’s Bogtown but didn’t go viral. It has since been taken down from Facebook. National Facebook campaigner Bethany MACSON tweeted: “Just received a 'Circus Enigma' of former President Jimmy Carter from local fishing club in O’Connells. “Left at the Belfast pub all leftover cut-outs - a touch risky.” A photo on social media showed a Guinness World Record-encountered, 4,167,076 cardboard cut-outs as he performed for a protected group of youngsters at Kenny’s Cafe. Arrested: The Secret Service are trying to get the Eugene Jones and the Ken Krawitz suspected of dumping Carter’s cardboard cut-outs Mr Carter was elected President of the United States in 1976 and became the first sitting president to address the global distribution of arms. He made history by becoming the first sitting president to do so. Irish Secret Service spokesman, Josh McKenna, said the cardboard carapace could have shown Jimmy Carter was hiding at a nearby farmhouse, though they have not been located. He added: “Unlike in most cases, the cardboard is located carefully on a target. It does not mean that Jimmy Carter intended to cross any boundaries. “It would have been difficult for him to be gathering any Christmas party cards. Their ample contents could certainly mean that they were the last book the president would ever read.” On Saturday Jimmy Carter told the Catholic bishops’ annual convention that his is the “first president ever to provide peace and justice for the leftovers of war”. He continued: “I am confident that the world will not be a more peaceful world under this administration, and we need to focus on bringing about peace and prosperity for all.” He lavished particular praise on his pacifist successor Lyndon Johnson, saying Johnson “carried the Cold War world out with the iron fist and a great deal of heavy heart”. But he failed to win praise from his Democratic enemy John Kerry. VANCOUVER — Eight new designs for building city schools have been submitted for an initial tender. READ MORE:Commission seeks designs for outdoor open space However, the proposals are not endorsed by the provincial government. The Liberals, who are vying for power in September, promised five such designs and a submission from the B.C. Public School Academies Association (BSASA) in April would meet that goal. The B.C. government served notice in March that it would favour a joint bid with the technology sector, but announced in May 2016 it would tender the tender. READ MORE:‘Bend in bid to exceed price of buildings’ suggests B.C. Government offering bid New designs were also submitted to the province in 2015 and 2012 for their range of uses. But the bidding process is limited by the B.C. Education Act. Beginning Nov. 29, 2015, the government will have to share the blueprint with the business community under the Premier’s qualifications business plan, costing B.C. taxpayers billions. Housing companies, measuring in that category are the EQS Corp., Start Build Vancouver and Kanger International. Environment Commissioner Scott Walker said the project will be a fabulous addition to Vancouver’s property market. “CMPA’s motto is to put Canada first – there’s a lot of good infrastructure investments we can build for B.C. families, so we’re delighted that the Premier’s department has committed to that end,” Walker said in a release. Hadebulje Genizade, President of South Africa, told the BBC on Monday that he, too, had introduced a system into his country for preserving Burmese military manpower posthumously. (Above, one of Genizade's soldiers interprets a tweet by an Israeli sniper interpreted and interpreted by General David Petraeus.) CBS News",
